original_title: Queens: Yellowstone Boulevard - Dartmouth Street & Clyde Street
text:
Yellowstone Boulevard, (Gable end of house to road formerly White Pot Road) east side between Dartmouth and Clyde Streets, showing in 4 views the Abraham Furman farmhouse said to be the Springsteen homestead, so claimed, because Casper Joost Springsteen settled in White Pot in 1700. See other views. Views 3 and 4 show also the side facing White Pot Road.

1922
Views 1,2 and 3
View 4: April 1923.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection

original_title: Queens: Yellowstone Boulevard - Dartmouth Street & Clyde Street
text:
Yellowstone Boulevard, east side, between Dartmouth and Clyde Streets, showing in a set of 4 views the Abraham Furman farmhouse. Gabriel Furman was the son of John Furman who died in 1726. He, John, owned this farm which was in 1852 in the possession of his great grandson Abraham. Some of the later owners were: Abraham Furman, 1852-1860; G. Furman, 1860-1873; Mrs. H. Miller, 1872-1891; and A. Miller from 1891 to 1909. The house was no longer standing in Aug. 1925. One Holzheiser was an occupant about 1873. See other views.

1922
Views 1, 2 3 and 4

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection
